---
import MainLayout from '../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import Link from '../../components/Link.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/TableOfContents.astro';
const title = 'Tree Asset Creation - Cities Skylines Modding';
import ResponsiveImage from '../../components/ResponsiveImage.astro';
import { images } from '../../data/imageImports.js';
---

<MainLayout title={title}>
	<TableOfContents />
	<section class="py-12 sm:ml-64 xl:mr-64 text-lg text-hit-gray-500">
		<div class="content">
			<h1 id="overview" class="border-b-4 border-hit-gray-600 pb-8 text-4xl font-bold text-hit-gray-400">Tree Asset Creation</h1>
			<h2 class="border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 mt-24 pb-8 text-4xl font-medium text-hit-gray-400" id="mesh">Mesh</h2>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="main-mesh">Main Mesh</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				This is a 3D model of the tree, which will be visible when the camera is close to it. The actual mesh file contains vertices (their coordinates, UV
				mapping, normals, and colors) and triangles.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">It's created using 3D modeling software such as Blender, 3ds Max, Maya or SketchUp.</p>
			<div class="flex gap-2 mt-6 items-start justify-start">
				<svg
					class="w-8 h-8 text-hoverlink flex-shrink-0"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path d="M12 9v3.75m9-.75a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0zm-9 3.75h.008v.008H12v-.008z" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic"><em> Unlike almost all other shaders, the tree shader is 2 sided, which means the back sides of faces are visible.</em></p>
			</div>
			<h4 class="text-xl text-hit-gray-400 font-medium border-b border-hit-gray-950 pb-4 mt-8 lg:mt-12" id="model-complexity">Model Complexity</h4>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						It's recommended to stay within reasonable triangle counts based on the size and detail of your model. You may look at examples of vanilla trees or
						assets by other creators for reference.
					</p><p class="mt-4">The absolute limit for a mesh is 65536 vertices.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/tree/treetris.jpg" target="_blank">
						<ResponsiveImage
							src={images.treetris}
							naturalHeight={437}
							naturalWidth={1488}
							srcWidths={[300, 400, 800, 1000]}
							alt="Triangle counts for a couple of vanilla trees"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="h-auto w-full aspect-video object-cover"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Triangle counts for a couple of vanilla trees.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="flex gap-2 mt-6 items-start justify-start">
				<svg
					class="w-8 h-8 text-hoverlink flex-shrink-0"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path d="M12 9v3.75m9-.75a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0zm-9 3.75h.008v.008H12v-.008z" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic">
					<em>
						You can use <Link
							classes=""
							href="https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=453956891"
							text="Mesh Info by SamsamTS"
							theme="externallink"
						/> to check triangle counts of assets.
					</em>
				</p>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="uv-mapping">UV Mapping</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>You are allowed to UV map outside the 0-1 area (main tile), so you can tile the entire texture multiple times on a single face.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/building/uv_main.jpg" target="_blank"
						><ResponsiveImage
							src={images.uv_main}
							naturalHeight={437}
							naturalWidth={560}
							srcWidths={[300, 400, 500]}
							alt="Example UV mapping using visible horizontal tiling on the bottom"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="h-auto w-full aspect-square object-cover"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Example UV mapping using visible horizontal tiling on the bottom.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="pivot-origin">Pivot / Origin</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The pivot point or origin represents the center point on the ground, where the tree will be plopped. It's usually represented using a red/green/blue
				axis gizmo.
			</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="transform">Transform</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Make sure you are exporting a single object, which doesn't have any rotation or scale.<br />This can be done using <Link
					classes=""
					href="https://wiki.blender.org/index.php/User:Fade/Doc:2.6/Manual/3D_interaction/Transform_Control/Reset_Object_Transformations#Apply_Object_transformations"
					text='"apply rotation & scale" in Blender'
					theme="externallink"
				/>, or <Link
					classes=""
					href="https://knowledge.autodesk.com/support/3ds-max/learn-explore/caas/CloudHelp/cloudhelp/2017/ENU/3DSMax/files/GUID-B98414B9-4F28-45F4-A1F4-9DA994548ED9-htm.html"
					text='"reset xform" in 3ds Max'
					theme="externallink"
				/>, and exporting only the selected object.
			</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="vertex-paint">Vertex Paint</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				For trees, vertex colors are automatically generated on import, they determine how much the tree will sway in the wind, you can reduce or disable this
				effect by running <Link classes="" href="https://gist.github.com/ronyx69/318eab7a17c9d6a38d123eba0cefaab7" text="this script" theme="externallink" /> in
				the <Link classes="" href="https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=450877484" text="ModTools" theme="externallink" />
				<span class="key">F7</span> console.
			</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="formats">Formats</h3>
			<ul class="mt-4 list-disc list-inside">
				<li class="mt-4">FBX (2015 or older) (most commonly used)</li>
				<li class="mt-4">OBJ (doesn't support vertex colors)</li>
				<li class="mt-4">DAE</li>
			</ul>
			<h2 class="border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 mt-24 pb-8 text-4xl font-medium text-hit-gray-400" id="textures">Textures</h2>
			<p class="mt-4">These determine the color and material properties of your tree.</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="resolution">Resolution</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">All imported main textures must be the same resolution.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Powers of 2 is a standard practice in 3D graphics, which means resolutions such as 1024x1024, 1024x512, 256x512, 2048x128 etc. It is recommended to
				stick to this standard, otherwise, your texture may be corrupted by compression, which may be more visible at longer distances or grazing angles. The
				smallest allowed resolution is 32x32.
			</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="diffuse">Diffuse</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>The main color and texture of your asset.</p><p class="mt-4">
						It will look very bright, contrasty, and saturated in the game, so make sure to reduce the saturation and limit the brightest parts to a
						medium/light gray below 140 RGB.
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import a diffuse map, it will default to white.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<div class="">
						<a href="/images/asset/tree/treetextures.jpg" target="_blank">
							<ResponsiveImage
								src={images.treetextures}
								naturalHeight={256}
								naturalWidth={384}
								srcWidths={[300, 350]}
								alt="Textures for a couple of vanilla trees"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full aspect-video object-cover"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Textures for a couple of vanilla trees.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="mt-4">
						<a href="/images/asset/building/color_guidelines.png" target="_blank"
							><ResponsiveImage
								src={images.color_guidelines}
								naturalHeight={1024}
								naturalWidth={1024}
								srcWidths={[300, 400, 800, 1000]}
								alt="Color guidelines"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full aspect-square object-cover"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Color guidelines.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="alpha">Alpha</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						Transparency, white means opaque or visible, black means transparent or invisible. Gray values may affect how it looks from a distance or at an
						angle.
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import an alpha map, it will default to fully opaque or fully visible.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<div class="">
						<a href="/images/asset/building/textures_alpha.jpg" target="_blank"
							><ResponsiveImage
								src={images.textures_alpha}
								naturalHeight={220}
								naturalWidth={306}
								srcWidths={[200, 300]}
								alt="Example alpha texture for some railings and metal beams"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full aspect-video object-cover"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Example alpha texture for some railings and metal beams.</p>
					</div><div class="mt-4">
						<a href="/images/asset/building/textures_alpha_rail.jpg" target="_blank">
							<ResponsiveImage
								src={images.textures_alpha_rail}
								naturalHeight={128}
								naturalWidth={256}
								srcWidths={[200, 250]}
								alt="Example alpha texture for some railings and metal beams"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full aspect-video"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">
							Using lighter values for the invisible parts will decrease the chance of small details like railings disappearing completely.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="color">Color</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">Determines which parts are leaves or branches/bark.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">The leaves should be black and the rest should be white.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">This allows for leaf brightness variation for each tree, snow on winter maps, and better-looking normals for 2 sided faces.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				If you don't import a color map, it will default to white, which means the normals for leaves will look weird and there won't be any snow on winter
				maps.
			</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="normal">Normal</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>Also sometimes called a bump map, adds fake depth or form by affecting how the lighting appears.</p><p class="mt-4">
						This can be made from the diffuse or a height map (brighter colors will look extruded out more) using <Link
							classes=""
							href="http://cpetry.github.io/NormalMap-Online/"
							text="a normal map generator online"
							theme="externallink"
						/>, a photoshop plugin like <Link classes="" href="http://www.xnormal.net/" text="xNormal" theme="externallink" />, or standalone software such as <Link
							classes=""
							href="https://www.crazybump.com/"
							text="CrazyBump"
							theme="externallink"
						/>.
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						The normal map generator should be set to +X +Y, which means no color channel inversions are required. Read more in the <Link
							classes=""
							href="/normal-maps/"
							text="normal map article"
							theme="internallink"
						/>.
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import a normal map, it will default to a flat normal map - no bump.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<div class="">
						<a href="/images/asset/tree/treenormal.jpg" target="_blank">
							<ResponsiveImage
								src={images.treenormal}
								naturalHeight={256}
								naturalWidth={256}
								srcWidths={[200, 250]}
								alt="Example normal map for a plant"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full aspect-square object-cover"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Example normal map for a plant.</p>
					</div><div class="mt-4">
						<a href="/images/asset/building/textures_normal_problem.jpg" target="_blank"
							><ResponsiveImage
								src={images.textures_normal_problem}
								naturalHeight={633}
								naturalWidth={981}
								srcWidths={[300, 400, 500, 600, 700, 800, 900]}
								alt="Example normal map problem"
								format="webp"
								sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
								class="h-auto w-full aspect-video"
								loading="eager"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Problem: normal maps appear incorrectly if the asset importer mesh rotation feature is used.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="format">Format</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">Use a lossless format like .PNG.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The game supports other formats as well, but there is no reason to use another one, it doesn't matter how much your texture is compressed or even if
				it's completely solid or complicated, the game will convert it to a DXT format, so the final size won't be affected by anything other than resolution.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Make sure the texture is 8 bits/channel because a 16 bits/channel image can't be imported. Do not use the "Smaller File (8-bit)" feature in the
				Photoshop Export As window, as that creates an indexed color image, not an 8 bits/channel one.
			</p>
			<div class="flex gap-2 mt-6 items-start justify-start">
				<svg
					class="w-8 h-8 text-orange flex-shrink-0"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path
						d="M12 9v3.75m-9.303 3.376c-.866 1.5.217 3.374 1.948 3.374h14.71c1.73 0 2.813-1.874 1.948-3.374L13.949 3.378c-.866-1.5-3.032-1.5-3.898 0L2.697 16.126zM12 15.75h.007v.008H12v-.008z"
						stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic">
					<em>
						Make sure texture quality is set to high in the game's graphics settings. otherwise, your imported textures will be downscaled to a lower
						resolution.
					</em>
				</p>
			</div>
			<h2 class="border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 mt-24 pb-8 text-4xl font-medium text-hit-gray-400" id="lod">LOD</h2>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Trees don't require an LOD, it's generated automatically ingame using a render texture and billboarding, and updates every time the camera is rotated.
			</p>
			<h2 class="border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 mt-24 pb-8 text-4xl font-medium text-hit-gray-400" id="import">Import</h2>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="naming">Naming</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">The mesh can have any name, but it's not recommended to use spaces or underscores.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The textures must have the same name as the mesh, but with the texture type identifier after it, so the result will be names like meshname_d.png.
			</p>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="import-folder">Import Folder</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>You should place the mesh and texture files in the import folder located here:</p><p class="mt-4">
						<span class="path">%LocalAppData%\Colossal Order\Cities_Skylines\Addons\Import</span>
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						The AppData folder is hidden by default, you can access it by copying and pasting the path into the file explorer, or pressing <span class="key"
							>Windows + R</span
						> and typing in appdata.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/tree/treeimportfolder.jpg" target="_blank">
						<ResponsiveImage
							src={images.treeimportfolder}
							naturalHeight={149}
							naturalWidth={459}
							srcWidths={[200, 300, 400]}
							alt="Files ready for import"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="h-auto w-full aspect-video object-cover"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Files ready for import.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="template">Template</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">The template you choose will determine some things about your tree:</p>
			<ul class="mt-4 list-disc list-inside">
				<li class="mt-4">create ruining (shows map theme ruined texture on the ground)</li>
				<li class="mt-4">max/min brightness</li>
				<li class="mt-4">max/min scale</li>
				<li class="mt-4">disable snow toggle</li>
			</ul>
			<div class="flex gap-2 mt-6 items-start justify-start">
				<svg
					class="w-8 h-8 text-hoverlink flex-shrink-0"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path d="M12 9v3.75m9-.75a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0zm-9 3.75h.008v.008H12v-.008z" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic">
					<em>
						All of those things can be changed later in the editor itself or using <Link
							classes=""
							href="https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=450877484"
							text="ModTools"
							theme="externallink"
						/> or other mods.
					</em>
				</p>
			</div>
			<h3 class="mt-16 text-2xl text-hit-gray-400 font-semibold border-b border-hit-gray-500 pb-4" id="import-1">Import</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-6 mt-4">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						After you choose your mesh, depending on how it was exported, you might need to set the correct scale and rotation, scale 100 and rotating 3 times
						around X-axis are common necessities.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/tree/treeimportmesh.jpg" target="_blank">
						<ResponsiveImage
							src={images.treeimportmesh}
							naturalHeight={533}
							naturalWidth={876}
							srcWidths={[300, 400, 500, 600, 800]}
							alt="Importing a mesh in asset importer"
							format="webp"
							sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 248px, (min-width: 1200px) 183px, (min-width: 1000px) 205px, (min-width: 780px) 448px, (min-width: 580px) 276px, calc(100vw - 48px)"
							class="h-auto w-full aspect-video object-cover"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Importing a mesh in asset importer.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="flex gap-2 mt-6 items-start justify-start">
				<svg
					class="w-8 h-8 text-orange flex-shrink-0"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path
						d="M12 9v3.75m-9.303 3.376c-.866 1.5.217 3.374 1.948 3.374h14.71c1.73 0 2.813-1.874 1.948-3.374L13.949 3.378c-.866-1.5-3.032-1.5-3.898 0L2.697 16.126zM12 15.75h.007v.008H12v-.008z"
						stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic">
					<em>
